<subSubSection id="838653126B807E75A24594D321758C28" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="B7E095C0336122370DE2E6EC7616D209" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="56841F1E5F138A60E76C2A763E175F11" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
the epithet refers to its 
<normalizedToken id="C58057902999DC7955FFD52A8BA1E2CA" originalValue="host–ant">host-ant</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A9A870D5DED3B21FAB0FFAE8C87A0E6B" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="holotype">
<paragraph id="C7C121E86CD35C3113C63CA5AA332BF2" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53DA76AD2339788E62C5B13779473C70" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">HKAS 102459; living culture: MFLUCC 18-1379.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2D3B32954AFD82E8728E8D4D9B45ADA4" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="description">
<paragraph id="93A6ACE39FAD999DED115125D24C3E3D" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EB9F7AACF46F980CC673C162A80FED6C" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
Parasitic on ant (
<taxonomicName id="7C8D31B49ED5326FF064E38D928AE8CB" authority="(B.Species)" authorityName="(B.Species)" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formicidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Formicidae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Formicidae</taxonomicName>
). 
<emphasis id="DD31DD84EF50C8C903B8F5DC56E211CD" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Asexual morph</emphasis>
: Hyphomycetous. 
<emphasis id="E5D68F3CF06613A1C89A6125B73811BB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Mycelium</emphasis>
rarely septate, hyaline, smooth-walled, covering the whole body of the ant host. 
<taxonomicName id="A17780716BFF41A0DE1C424B41272F1D" genus="Synnemata" lsidName="Synnemata" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F29D442CEAC13675C66147BBC97DABB2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Synnemata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
250-350 
<normalizedToken id="EDF50CDED27655D5AB84976E03CF1526" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
65-100 (xˉ = 300 
<normalizedToken id="68913D0442C9C1A8679FE0A6724CEC7F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
86, n = 10) 
<normalizedToken id="88095AF6BE1BEC25B2D0CE68C4E36F51" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, forming at the head region of ant host in circular arrangement, flask-shaped, hyaline to yellowish, composed of dense hyphae, somehow curved. 
<emphasis id="32933E6716D52296ADA69040B92CA804" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Phialides</emphasis>
25-100 
<normalizedToken id="C6D144857529C5352D040E676DAF8A00" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-1.5 (xˉ = 49 
<normalizedToken id="112E94AC72C19B5600A3C42C01312AB4" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.1, n = 20) 
<normalizedToken id="612669F21B065399203249E10A359D53" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, arising from procumbent hyphae or synnemata, blastic, enteroblastic, phialidic, monophialidic, discrete, terminal, unbranched, solitary, aseptate, hyaline, smooth-walled, slender, occasionally a swollen node present. 
<emphasis id="D26AFD12FADF70D1B46432ABB0BD6378" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Conidia</emphasis>
2-3.5 
<normalizedToken id="8E7E4517DAC27FBB133752310E782586" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5-2.5 (xˉ = 2.6 
<normalizedToken id="BD6D88B642BF768721EC9C8EA6C3FA2D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2, n = 30) 
<normalizedToken id="0A10704B323FD10ADF1FCC1F34E3AD8D" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, globose to ellipsoidal, hyaline, one-celled, smooth-walled, round at both ends, adhering in slimy head on the tip of phialides. 
<emphasis id="048A24E6CFF9D8E352AEFD574B614EB6" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Sexual morph</emphasis>
: Undetermined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62AC77E3F88FF7D51E5110A894B3EE94" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="description">
<paragraph id="B96B9869991860CEE8E4F6B71C40FCC2" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Culture characteristics.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25E578FC7CD133F977D7A48AADA2EE2F" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
The colonies were rapid-growing on PDA medium, reaching a diameter of 2.5-3 (xˉ = 2.6, n = 9) cm, in 13 days at 22 °C, entire margin, circular, velvety and white from above, with radial crack and primrose-yellow on reverse. 
<emphasis id="DC4F7CED7A212D063D52C24BFDE2B81F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">In vitro</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A82A078715D22F96D56A58B7FF78F6E3" genus="Synnemata" lsidName="Synnemata" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6A0F15CB675C0A621B1037249F81E391" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Synnemata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
absent. 
<emphasis id="1E44318C123908FA99DF10E9F2143DDA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Phialides</emphasis>
25-75 
<normalizedToken id="597E9456D23856C22876597C60C40078" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.4-0.6 (xˉ = 50 
<normalizedToken id="64E88C38B0D601B03D9B71E69D322C24" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.55, n = 10) 
<normalizedToken id="362636EB1DB26BA006D51AB40A8C0764" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, arising from procumbent hyphae, blastic, enteroblastic, phialidic, discrete, terminal, unbranched, solitary, aseptate, hyaline, smooth-walled, relatively slender and long. 
<emphasis id="70B4A080752E792D2421CDF6189FF661" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Conidia</emphasis>
1.5-3 
<normalizedToken id="2F69247A7016D2B956A48E8B6B0A598F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5-2.5 (xˉ = 2.3 
<normalizedToken id="DC6AD3EFEE08163939BD2B97A322E0A0" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.7, n = 100) 
<normalizedToken id="D5F3DCC9B5ADA6BF4312D615B7936361" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, hyaline, globose to ellipsoidal, aseptate, smooth-walled, slightly guttulate, adhering in slimy head on the tip of phialides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3C9EAE865277371F32BC90E5695066F8" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="186945EAB6D7FD10D04597924D2C86BB" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Material examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="13E2B1C756D1045A5246A3FD3C3F82B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
THAILAND, Chiang Mai Province, Mushroom Research Centre, on an adult ant, 1 April 2018, 
<emphasis id="3BA2D07E99F6D174F0B49A5499638AB3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Deping Wei</emphasis>
, MRC18040102 (
<emphasis id="797887590F8D6BD7BA40459561611232" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">holotype</emphasis>
: HKAS 102459; 
<emphasis id="A6BC7D3A5B92387D5C932D7FEE982EE1" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">ex-type living culture</emphasis>
: MFLUCC 18-1379). Sequences generated from this strain have been deposited in GenBank with accession numbers: SSU = MK765046, LSU = MK766512, ITS = MK766511, TEF = MK926451, RPB1 = MK882623.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="565CD9EFABC6E347385D6AEE46267521" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="notes">
<paragraph id="6F35C7B5960149298942DC7F38397E57" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="30DADD698439F60ED462DAF7B9AAC65E" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
Isolate MFLUCC 18-1379 has a close phylogenetic relationship with 
<taxonomicName id="992A0944D410F7C577DE87A82C2937FC" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Simplicillium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Simplicillium obclavatum" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="obclavatum">
<emphasis id="D8B631049FFF2C981D90532BA7403946" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Simplicillium obclavatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on ITS sequence analysis. The new isolate is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="783AF582A4A889188651DEC1BE398FEF" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Simplicillium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Simplicillium obclavatum" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="obclavatum">
<emphasis id="3536B9CA3172414E8D12281C70F1B1B1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Simplicillium obclavatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in terms of shape and dimensions of the conidia with slender phialides tapering towards the apex. However, they have a different conidial arrangement, by 
<taxonomicName id="85A47317BB30DA24D16DFE3A1E9D0D61" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Simplicillium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Simplicillium obclavatum" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="obclavatum">
<emphasis id="5BB8CF0C3CE3DB065BCC717EC45B0906" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Simplicillium obclavatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having short-imbricate chains, whereas the new fungus has subglobose to globose head. There are numerous synnemata in a circular arrangement which can be observed in our isolate and those are absent in 
<taxonomicName id="637C56CEB9BA8B969D7032D0493F573F" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Simplicillium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Simplicillium obclavatum" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="obclavatum">
<emphasis id="E49DB4A4027FE5D659939C715F6C1CFC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Simplicillium obclavatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The comparisons of ITS sequences between our isolate MFLUCC 18-1379 and ex-type strain of 
<taxonomicName id="C11896EFBADE338A548760B876E65347" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Simplicillium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Simplicillium obclavatum" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="obclavatum">
<emphasis id="D85F82AC305E239F04F85AE2750AA2D1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Simplicillium obclavatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(CBS 311.74) show 23 bp differences within 550 bp (4.2%). Thereby, we identify our isolates as a new species according to 
<bibRefCitation id="3791DA4FBF54DD7F51698C0C45024550" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5943/mycosphere/7/11/4" author="Jeewon, R" journalOrPublisher="Mycosphere" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1669 - 1677" refId="B24" refString="Jeewon, R, Hyde, KD, 2016. Establishing species boundaries and new taxa among fungi: recommendations to resolve taxonomic ambiguities. Mycosphere 7: 1669 - 1677" title="Establishing species boundaries and new taxa among fungi: recommendations to resolve taxonomic ambiguities." url="https://doi.org/10.5943/mycosphere/7/11/4" volume="7" year="2016">Jeewon and Hyde (2016)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
